ce Digital TV. The operator was acquired by Pantel Technologies & Veecon Media in January 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/corporate/rcom-big-tv-pantel-tech-veecon-media-buying-anil-ambani-dth-business/story/264955.html|title=RCom seals deal to sell off BIG TV: Pantel Tech, Veecon Media buying Anil Ambani's DTH business|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=2018-05-25}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, the company launched a pre-booking DTH offer. The company took bookings and collected revenue from customers, but the service connections were not installed.<ref>{{cite news |title= Reliance Big TV Offers Free Access To Channels. Here's How To Avail It| first=profit team |last=NDTV |url=https://www.ndtv.com/business/reliance-big-tv-offer-how-to-watch-free-hd-channels-for-1-year-1818737 |newspaper=NDTV|publisher=New Delhi Television Media group |location=India |date= 21 March 2018|accessdate= 19 August 2018 }}</ref> After launching the DTH offer, the Pantel Technologies & Veecon Media group rebrand the company as Independent TV.<ref>{{cite news |title= Reliance Big tv Is Now Independent Tv| first= adithya |last=DTHForum |url=https://dthforum.com/threads/reliance-big-tv-is-now-independent-tv.49349/|publisher=DTHForum |location=India |date= 28 July 2018|accessdate= 24 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe company was unable to provide installation to customers since their agreement with [[Star India|STAR India group]] had expired due to nonpayment. On 23 July 2018, [[Telecom Disputes Settlement and Appellate Tribunal]] (TDSAT) requested Star India and Independent TV to enter into a fresh agreement within 4 weeks.<ref>{{cite news |title= TDSAT asks STAR India and Independent TV to enter into fresh agreement within 4 weeks| first= TVP Bureau|last=Television Post|url=https://www.televisionpost.com/tdsat-asks-star-india-independent-tv-to-enter-into-fresh-agreement-within-4-weeks/|publisher=Television Post|location=India |date= July 23, 2018|accessdate= 24 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe company's service was disrupted after further payments to the Antrix corporation were missed. Independent TV closed its services on 12 June 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sharma |first1=Arpit |title=Independent TV Subscribers Face Disruption as Company Fails to Pay Dues |url=https://telecomtalk.info/independent-tv-disruption/200271/ |website=telecomtalk |accessdate=24 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIndependent TV Limited is a DTH Licensee of the Ministry of Information & Broadcasting (MIB), Govt of India. This license has been renewed on June 19, 2019 for a further period of six (6) months, like for all other DTH licensees in India today, and is valid till Dec 31, 2019. All the conditions precedents defined by MIB, Govt of India, have already been successfully complied with, and acknowledged as of July 5, 2019. The satellite services of the DTH operator are temporarily suspended. Independent TV limited has launched a new go-to-market business drive named \u201cITV 2.0\u201d for its channel partners, to resume its Business Operations again for consumer acquisition and service delivery<ref name=\"TT1\">{{cite web |last1=Kudikala |first1=Chakri |title=ITV 2.0 Aka Independent TV to Restore DTH Operations on August 15 |url=https://telecomtalk.info/independent-tv-august-resumption/212701/ |website=Telecom Talk |publisher=Telecom Talk |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> As of January 2020, with TRAI's The Indian Telecom Services Performance Indicator Report July \u2013 September 2019, it has acknowledge that Independent TV has fully shut down operations taking the count of pay dth operators to four.<ref name=\"TT2\">{{cite news |last1=Kudikala |first1=Chakri |title=Independent TV Shuts Down Services, Total Pay DTH Operator Count Becomes 4 in India: Trai |url=https://telecomtalk.info/independent-tv-closed-dth-operations/242740/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=Telecom Talk |publisher=telecomtalk.info |date=9 January 2020 |language=English}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Direct-to-home television in India]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website|http://singhamtv.rf.gd/}}\n\n{{DTH in India}}\n{{Reliance Anil Dhirubhai Ambani Group}}\n\n[[Category:Reliance Anil Dhirubhai Ambani Group]]\n[[Category:Indian direct broadcast satellite services]]\n[[Category:Indian television networks]]\n[[Category:Indian brands]]\n", "name_user": "Agrayh", "label": "safe", "comment": "Website", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independent_TV_(India)"}
{"title_page": "FtsZ", "text_new": "{{Pfam box\n|Name=Cell division protein FtsZ|Symbol=FtsZ\n|CDD=cd02201|InterPro=IPR000158|CATH=1fsz|SCOP=1fsz}}\n{{Pfam box\n|Name=FtsZ, C-terminal sandwich|Symbol=FtsZ_C\n|InterPro=IPR024757|Pfam=PF12327}}\n{{Infobox nonhuman protein|image=PDB 1fsz EBI.jpg|caption=Molecular Structure of FtsZ (PDB 1fsz).|UniProt=P0A9A6|Organism=''Escherichia coli''|Name=Cell division protein FtsZ|Symbol=ftsZ}}\n'''FtsZ''' is a [[protein]] encoded by the ''ftsZ'' [[gene]] that assembles into a ring at the future site of [[bacterial]] [[cell division]]. FtsZ is a [[prokaryotic]] [[Homology (biology)|homologue]] of the [[eukaryotic]] protein [[tubulin]]. The initials FtsZ mean \"'''F'''ilamenting  '''t'''emperature-'''s'''ensitive mutant '''Z'''\". The hypothesis was that cell division mutants of ''[[E. coli]]'' would grow as [[filamentation|filaments]] due to the inability of the daughter cells to separate from one another. FtsZ is found in almost all bacteria, many archaea, all chloroplasts and some mitochondria, where it is essential for cell division. FtsZ assembles the cytoskeletal scaffold of the Z ring that, along with additional proteins, constricts to divide the cell in two. \n\n== History ==\nIn the 1960s scientists screened for temperature sensitive mutations that blocked cell division at 42\u00b0 C. The mutant cells divided normally at 30\u00b0, but failed to divide at 42\u00b0. Continued growth without division produced long filamentous cells ('''F'''ilamenting '''t'''emperature '''s'''ensitive). Several such mutants were discovered and mapped to a locus originally named ''ftsA,'' which could be one or more genes''.'' In 1980 Lutkenhaus and Donachie<ref name=\"pmid6991482\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Lutkenhaus JF, Wolf-Watz H, Donachie WD | title = Organization of genes in the ftsA-envA region of the Escherichia coli genetic map and identification of a new fts locus (ftsZ) | journal = Journal of Bacteriology | volume = 142 | issue = 2 | pages = 615\u201320 | date = May 1980 | pmid = 6991482 | pmc = 294035 | url = https://jb.asm.org/content/jb/142/2/615.full.pdf | oclc = 678550294 }}</ref> showed that several of these mutations mapped to one gene, ''ftsA,'' but one well-characterized mutant, PAT84, originally discovered by Hirota et al,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hirota Y, Ryter A, Jacob F | title = Thermosensitive mutants of ''E. coli'' affected in the processes of DNA synthesis and cellular division | journal = Cold Spring Harbor Symposia on Quantitative Biology | volume = 33 | pages = 677\u201393 | date = 1968-01-01 | pmid = 4892005 | doi = 10.1101/sqb.1968.033.01.077 }}</ref> mapped to a separate, adjacent gene. They named this cell division gene ''ftsZ.'' In 1991 Bi and [[Joe Lutkenhaus|Lutkenhaus]] used immunogold electron microscopy to show that FtsZ localized to the invaginating septum at midcell.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Bi EF, Lutkenhaus J | title = FtsZ ring structure associated with division in ''Escherichia coli'' | journal = Nature | volume = 354 | issue = 6349 | pages = 161\u20134 | date = November 1991 | pmid = 1944597 | doi = 10.1038/354161a0 }}</ref>  Subsequently, the Losick and Margolin groups used immuno-fluorescence microscopy<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Levin PA, Losick R | title = Transcription factor Spo0A switches the localization of the cell division protein FtsZ from a medial to a bipolar pattern in Bacillus subtilis | journal = Genes & Development | volume = 10 | issue = 4 | pages = 478\u201388 | date = February 1996 | pmid = 8600030 | doi = 10.1101/gad.10.4.478 }}</ref> and GFP fusions<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ma X, Ehrhardt DW, Margolin W | title = Colocalization of cell division proteins FtsZ and FtsA to cytoskeletal structures in living ''Escherichia coli'' cells by using green fluorescent protein | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 93 | issue = 23 | pages = 12998\u20133003 | date = November 1996 | pmid = 8917533 | pmc = 24035 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.93.23.12998 }}</ref> to show that FtsZ assembled Z rings early in the cell cycle, well before the septum began to constrict.  Other division proteins then assemble onto the Z ring and constriction occurs in the last part of the cell cycle.\n\nIn 1992-3 three labs independently discovered that FtsZ was related to eukaryotic tubulin, which is the protein subunit that assembles into microtubules<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = RayChaudhuri D, Park JT | title = ''Escherichia coli'' cell-division gene ftsZ encodes a novel GTP-binding protein | journal = Nature | volume = 359 | issue = 6392 | pages = 251\u20134 | date = September 1992 | pmid = 1528267 | doi = 10.1038/359251a0 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = de Boer P, Crossley R, Rothfield L | title = The essential bacterial cell-division protein FtsZ is a GTPase | journal = Nature | volume = 359 | issue = 6392 | pages = 254\u20136 | date = September 1992 | pmid = 1528268 | doi = 10.1038/359254a0 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Mukherjee A, Dai K, Lutkenhaus J | title = ''Escherichia coli'' cell division protein FtsZ is a guanine nucleotide binding protein | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 90 | issue = 3 | pages = 1053\u20137 | date = February 1993 | pmid = 8430073 | pmc = 45809 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.90.3.1053 }}</ref>. This was the first discovery that bacteria have homologs of eukaryotic cytoskeletal proteins. Later work showed that FtsZ was present in, and essential for cell division, in almost all bacteria and in many but not all archaea. \n\nMitochondria and chloroplasts are eukaryotic orgenelles that originated as bacterial endosymbionts, so there was much interest in whether they use FtsZ for division. Chloroplast FtsZ was first discovered by Osteryoung<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Osteryoung KW, Vierling E | title = Conserved cell and organelle division | journal = Nature | volume = 376 | issue = 6540 | pages = 473\u20134 | date = August 1995 | pmid = 7637778 | doi = 10.1038/376473b0 }}</ref>, and it is now known that all chloroplasts use FtsZ for division. Mitochondrial FtsZ was discovered by Beech<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beech|first=P. L.|date=2000-02-18|title=Mitochondrial FtsZ in a Chromophyte Alga|journal=Science|volume=287|issue=5456|pages=1276\u20131279|doi=10.1126/science.287.5456.1276|pmid=10678836|issn=0036-8075|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/1dff1339f803c1e0a730c910886add8023d3ef34}}</ref> in an alga; FtsZ is used for mitochondrial division in some eukaryotes, while others have replaced it with a dynamin-based machinery. \u00a0\n\n== Function ==\n[[File:Filamentation 1.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Inhibition of FtsZ disrupts septum formation, resulting in [[filamentation]] of bacterial cells (top right of electron micrograph).]]\n\nDuring [[cell division]], FtsZ is the first protein to move to the division site, and is essential for recruiting other proteins that produce a new [[cell wall]] ([[Septum (cell biology)|septum]]) between the dividing cells.  FtsZ's role in cell division is analogous to that of [[actin]] in eukaryotic cell division, but, unlike the [[actin]]-[[myosin]] ring in eukaryotes, FtsZ has no known [[motor protein]] associated with it.  The origin of the [[cytokinesis|cytokinetic]] force, thus, remains unclear, but it is believed that the localized synthesis of new cell wall produces at least part of this force.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors = Coltharp C, Buss J, Plumer TM, Xiao, J |display-authors = 4 | title = Defining the rate-limiting processes of bacterial cytokinesis | journal = PNAS | volume = 113 | issue = 8 | pages = e1044-e1053 | date = February 2016 | pmid = 26831086 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.1514296113 }}</ref>   In liposomes Osawa (2009) showed FtsZ is capable of exerting a contractile force with no other proteins present.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Osawa M, Anderson DE, Erickson HP | title = Reconstitution of contractile FtsZ rings in liposomes | journal = Science | volume = 320 | issue = 5877 | pages = 792\u20134 | date = May 2008 | pmid = 18420899 | pmc = 2645864 | doi = 10.1126/science.1154520 }}</ref>\n\nErickson (2009) proposed how the roles of tubulin-like proteins and actin-like proteins in cell division became reversed in an evolutionary mystery.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Erickson HP | title = Evolution of the cytoskeleton | journal = BioEssays | volume = 29 | issue = 7 | pages = 668\u201377 | date = July 2007 | pmid = 17563102 | pmc = 2630885 | doi = 10.1002/bies.20601 }}</ref>\nThe use of the FtsZ ring in dividing [[chloroplast]]s and some [[mitochondrion|mitochondria]] further establishes their prokaryotic ancestry.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Leger MM, Petr\u016f M, \u017d\u00e1rsk\u00fd V, Eme L, Vl\u010dek \u010c, Harding T, Lang BF, Eli\u00e1\u0161 M, Dole\u017eal P, Roger AJ | display-authors = 6 | title = An ancestral bacterial division system is widespread in eukaryotic mitochondria | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 112 | issue = 33 | pages = 10239\u201346 | date = August 2015 | pmid = 25831547 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.1421392112 | pmc = 4547283 }}</ref> [[L-form bacteria]] that lack a [[cell wall]] do not require FtsZ for division, which implies that bacteria may have retained components of an ancestral mode of cell division.<ref name=\"pmid123455\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Leaver M, Dom\u00ednguez-Cuevas P, Coxhead JM, Daniel RA, Errington J | title = Life without a wall or division machine in Bacillus subtilis | journal = Nature | volume = 457 | issue = 7231 | pages = 849\u201353 | date = February 2009 | pmid = 19212404 | doi = 10.1038/nature07742 }}</ref>\n\nMuch is known about the dynamic polymerization activities of [[tubulin]] and [[microtubules]], but little is known about these activities in FtsZ.  While it is known that single-stranded [[tubulin]] protofilaments form into 13 stranded [[microtubules]], the multistranded structure of the FtsZ-containing Z-ring is not known. It is only speculated that the structure consists of overlapping protofilaments.  Nevertheless, recent work with purified FtsZ on supported lipid bilayers as well as imaging FtsZ in living bacterial cells  revealed that FtsZ protofilaments have polarity and move in one direction by [[treadmilling]] <ref name=\"pmid24316672\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Loose M, Mitchison TJ | title = The bacterial cell division proteins FtsA and FtsZ self-organize into dynamic cytoskeletal patterns | journal = Nature Cell Biology | volume = 16 | issue = 1 | pages = 38\u201346 | date = January 2014 | pmid = 24316672 | pmc = 4019675 | doi = 10.1038/ncb2885 }}</ref>(see also below).\n\nRecently, proteins similar to tubulin and FtsZ have been discovered in large plasmids found in ''Bacillus'' species. They are believed to function as components of [[segrosome]]s, which are multiprotein complexes that partition chromosomes/plasmids in bacteria. The plasmid homologs of tubulin/FtsZ seem to have conserved the ability to polymerize into filaments.\n\n=== The contractile ring ===\n[[File:FtsZ Filaments.svg|thumb|right|The Z-ring forms from smaller subunits of FtsZ filaments. These filaments may pull on each other and tighten to divide the cell.]]\n[[File:Zrings.png|thumb|upright|right|[[Super-resolution imaging|Super-resolution]] image of Z-rings (green) at different stages of constriction in two ''E. coli'' cells.]]\nFtsZ has the ability to bind to [[Guanosine triphosphate|GTP]] and also exhibits a [[GTPase]] domain that allows it to hydrolyze GTP to GDP and a phosphate group. ''In vivo'', FtsZ forms filaments with a repeating arrangement of subunits, all arranged head-to-tail.<ref name=\"pmid9442869\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Desai A, Mitchison TJ | title = Microtubule polymerization dynamics | journal = Annual Review of Cell and Developmental Biology | volume = 13 | pages = 83\u2013117 | year = 1997 | pmid = 9442869 | doi = 10.1146/annurev.cellbio.13.1.83 }}</ref> These filaments form a ring around the longitudinal midpoint, or septum, of the cell. This ring is called the Z-ring.\n\nThe GTP hydrolyzing activity of the protein is not essential to the formation of filaments or cell division. Mutants defective in GTPase activity often still divide, but sometimes form twisted and disordered septa.  It is unclear as to whether FtsZ actually provides the physical force that results in division or serves as a marker for other proteins to execute division.\n\nIf FtsZ does provide force that divides the cell, it may do so through the relative movement of subunits. Computer models and ''in vivo'' measurements suggest that single FtsZ filaments cannot sustain a length more than 30 subunits long. In this model, FtsZ scission force comes from the relative lateral movement of subunits.<ref name=\"pmid19116281\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Lan G, Daniels BR, Dobrowsky TM, Wirtz D, Sun SX | title = Condensation of FtsZ filaments can drive bacterial cell division | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 106 | issue = 1 | pages = 121\u20136 | date = January 2009 | pmid = 19116281 | pmc = 2629247 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0807963106 }}</ref> Lines of FtsZ would line up together parallel and pull on each other creating a \"cord\" of many strings that tightens itself.\n\nIn other models, FtsZ does not provide the contractile force but provides the cell a spatial scaffold for other proteins to execute the division of the cell. This is akin to the creating of a temporary structure by construction workers to access hard-to-reach places of a building. The temporary structure allows unfettered access and ensures that the workers can reach all places. If the temporary structure is not correctly built, the workers will not be able to reach certain places, and the building will be deficient.\n\nThe scaffold theory is supported by information that shows that the formation of the ring and localization to the membrane requires the concerted action of a number of accessory proteins. ZipA or the actin homologue [[FtsA]] permit initial FtsZ localization to the membrane.<ref name=\"pmid15752196\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Pichoff S, Lutkenhaus J | title = Tethering the Z ring to the membrane through a conserved membrane targeting sequence in FtsA | journal = Molecular Microbiology | volume = 55 | issue = 6 | pages = 1722\u201334 | date = March 2005 | pmid = 15752196 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2958.2005.04522.x }}</ref>  Following localization to the membrane, division proteins of the Fts family are recruited for ring assembly.<ref name=\"pmid12457697\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Buddelmeijer N, Beckwith J | title = Assembly of cell division proteins at the ''E. coli'' cell center | journal = Current Opinion in Microbiology | volume = 5 | issue = 6 | pages = 553\u20137 | date = December 2002 | pmid = 12457697 | doi = 10.1016/S1369-5274(02)00374-0 }}</ref> Many of these proteins, such as FtsW, FtsK, and FtsQ are involved in stabilization of the Z ring and may also be active participants in the scission event. The timing of Z-ring formation suggests the possibility of a spatial or temporal signal that permits the formation of FtsZ filaments.\n\nRecent super-resolution imaging in several species supports a dynamic scaffold model, in which small clusters of FtsZ protofilaments or protofilament bundles move unidirectionally around the ring's circumference by treadmilling, anchored to the membrane by [[FtsA]] and other FtsZ-specific membrane tethers.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Yang X, Lyu Z, Miguel A, McQuillen R, Huang KC, Xiao J | title = GTPase activity-coupled treadmilling of the bacterial tubulin FtsZ organizes septal cell wall synthesis | journal = Science | volume = 355 | issue = 6326 | pages = 744\u2013747 | date = February 2017 | pmid = 28209899 | doi = 10.1126/science.aak9995 | pmc = 5851775 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Bisson-Filho AW, Hsu YP, Squyres GR, Kuru E, Wu F, Jukes C, Sun Y, Dekker C, Holden S, VanNieuwenhze MS, Brun YV, Garner EC | display-authors = 6 | title = Treadmilling by FtsZ filaments drives peptidoglycan synthesis and bacterial cell division | journal = Science | volume = 355 | issue = 6326 | pages = 739\u2013743 | date = February 2017 | pmid = 28209898 | pmc = 5485650 | doi = 10.1126/science.aak9973 }}</ref>  The speed of treadmilling depends on the rate of GTP hydrolysis within the FtsZ protofilaments, but in ''[[Escherichia coli]]'', synthesis of the division septum remains the rate limiting step for cytokinesis.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors = Coltharp C, Buss J, Plumer TM, Xiao, J |display-authors = 4 | title = Defining the rate-limiting processes of bacterial cytokinesis | journal = PNAS | volume = 113 | issue = 8 | pages = e1044-e1053 | date = February 2016 | pmid = 26831086 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.1514296113 }}</ref> The treadmilling action of FtsZ is required for proper synthesis of the division septum by septal peptidoglycan synthesis enzymes, suggesting that these enzymes can track the growing ends of the filaments.\n\n=== Septal localization and intracellular signaling ===\n\nThe formation of the Z-ring closely coincides with cellular processes associated with replication. Z-ring formation coincides with the termination of genome replication in ''E. coli'' and 70% of chromosomal replication in ''[[B. subtilis]]''.<ref name=\"pmid11254978\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Harry EJ | title = Coordinating DNA replication with cell division: lessons from outgrowing spores | journal = Biochimie | volume = 83 | issue = 1 | pages = 75\u201381 | date = January 2001 | pmid = 11254978 | doi = 10.1016/S0300-9084(00)01220-7 }}</ref> The timing of Z-ring formation suggests the possibility of a spatial or temporal signal that permits the formation of FtsZ filaments. In ''[[Escherichia coli]]'', at least two negative regulators of FtsZ assembly form a bipolar gradient, such that the critical concentration of FtsZ required for FtsZ assembly is lowest at mid-cell between the two segregating chromosomes.  This type of regulation seems to occur in other species such as ''[[Bacillus subtilis]]'' and ''[[Caulobacter crescentus]]''.  However, other species including ''[[Streptococcus pneumoniae]]'' and ''[[Myxococcus xanthus]]'' seem to use positive regulators that stimulate FtsZ assembly at mid-cell.<ref name=\"pmid26029202\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Rowlett VW, Margolin W | title = The Min system and other nucleoid-independent regulators of Z ring positioning | journal = Frontiers in Microbiology | volume = 6 | issue =  | pages = 478 | year = 2015 | pmid = 26029202 | pmc = 4429545 | doi = 10.3389/fmicb.2015.00478 }}</ref>\n\n=== Communicating distress ===\n\nFtsZ polymerization is also linked to stressors like [[DNA damage]]. DNA damage induces a variety of proteins to be manufactured, one of them called [[SulA]].<ref name=\"pmid16310415\">{{cite journal | vauthors = He AS, Rohatgi PR, Hersh MN, Rosenberg SM | title = Roles of ''E. coli'' double-strand-break-repair proteins in stress-induced mutation | journal = DNA Repair | volume = 5 | issue = 2 | pages = 258\u201373 | date = February 2006 | pmid = 16310415 | pmc = 3685484 | doi = 10.1016/j.dnarep.2005.10.006 }}</ref>  SulA prevents the polymerization and GTPase activity of FtsZ. SulA accomplishes this task by binding to self-recognizing FtsZ sites. By sequestering FtsZ, the cell can directly link DNA damage to inhibiting cell division.<ref name=\"pmid9430638\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Mukherjee A, Lutkenhaus J | title = Dynamic assembly of FtsZ regulated by GTP hydrolysis | journal = The EMBO Journal | volume = 17 | issue = 2 | pages = 462\u20139 | date = January 1998 | pmid = 9430638 | pmc = 1170397 | doi = 10.1093/emboj/17.2.462 }}</ref>\n\n=== Preventing DNA damage ===\n\nLike SulA, there are other mechanisms that prevent cell division that would result in disrupted genetic information sent to daughter cells. So far, two proteins have been identified in ''E. coli'' and ''B. subtilis'' that prevent division over the nucleoid region: Noc and [[SlmA]]. Noc [[gene knockout]]s result in cells that divide without respect to the [[nucleoid]] region, resulting in its asymmetrical partitioning between the daughter cells. The mechanism is not well understood, but thought to involve sequestration of FtsZ, preventing [[polymerization]] over the nucleoid region.<ref name=\"pmid15210112\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Wu LJ, Errington J | title = Coordination of cell division and chromosome segregation by a nucleoid occlusion protein in Bacillus subtilis | journal = Cell | volume = 117 | issue = 7 | pages = 915\u201325 | date = June 2004 | pmid = 15210112 | doi = 10.1016/j.cell.2004.06.002 }}</ref> The mechanism used by SlmA to inhibit FtsZ polymerization over the nucleoid <ref name=\"pmid15916962\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Bernhardt TG, de Boer PA | title = SlmA, a nucleoid-associated, FtsZ binding protein required for blocking septal ring assembly over Chromosomes in ''E. coli'' | journal = Molecular Cell | volume = 18 | issue = 5 | pages = 555\u201364 | date = May 2005 | pmid = 15916962 | doi = 10.1016/j.molcel.2005.04.012 | pmc = 4428309 }}</ref> is better understood, and uses two separate steps.  One domain of SlmA binds to a FtsZ polymer, then a separate domain of SlmA severs the polymer <ref name=\"pmid25078077\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Du S, Lutkenhaus J | title = SlmA antagonism of FtsZ assembly employs a two-pronged mechanism like MinCD | journal = PLoS Genetics | volume = 10 | issue = 7 | pages = e1004460 | date = July 2014 | pmid = 25078077 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pgen.1004460 | pmc = 4117426 }}</ref>.  A similar mechanism is thought to be used by MinC, another inhibitor of FtsZ polymerization involved in positioning of the FtsZ ring.<ref name=\"pmid20132438\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Shen B, Lutkenhaus J | title = Examination of the interaction between FtsZ and MinCN in ''E. coli'' suggests how MinC disrupts Z rings | journal = Molecular Microbiology | volume = 75 | issue = 5 | pages = 1285\u201398 | date = March 2010 | pmid = 20132438 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2958.2010.07055.x }}</ref>\n\n== Clinical significance ==\n\nThe number of multidrug-resistant bacterial strains is currently increasing; thus, the determination of drug targets for the development of novel antimicrobial drugs is urgently needed. The potential role of FtsZ in the blockage of cell division makes FtsZ a highly attractive target for developing novel antibiotics. Researchers have been working on synthetic molecules and natural products as inhibitors of FtsZ.<ref name=\":32020845\">{{ Cite journal |title =A key bacterial cytoskeletal cell division protein FtsZ as a novel therapeutic antibacterial drug target|author1=ur Rahman, M. |author2=Wang, P. |author3=Wang, N. |author4=Chen, Y. |journal = Bosnian Journal of Basic Medical Science|year =2020|volume =|issue =|pages =|pmid =32020845|doi =10.17305/bjbms.2020.4597|url=https://bjbms.org/ojs/index.php/bjbms/article/view/4597/1301}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Fission (biology)]]\n* [[Divisome]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cytoskeletal Proteins}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ftsz}}\n[[Category:Bacterial proteins]]\n[[Category:Cytoskeleton]]\n", "text_old": "{{Pfam box\n|Name=Cell division protein FtsZ|Symbol=FtsZ\n|CDD=cd02201|InterPro=IPR000158|CATH=1fsz|SCOP=1fsz}}\n{{Pfam box\n|Name=FtsZ, C-terminal sandwich|Symbol=FtsZ_C\n|InterPro=IPR024757|Pfam=PF12327}}\n{{Infobox nonhuman protein|image=PDB 1fsz EBI.jpg|caption=Molecular Structure of FtsZ (PDB 1fsz).|UniProt=P0A9A6|Organism=''Escherichia coli''|Name=Cell division protein FtsZ|Symbol=ftsZ}}\n'''FtsZ''' is a [[protein]] encoded by the ''ftsZ'' [[gene]] that assembles into a ring at the future site of [[bacterial]] [[cell division]]. FtsZ is a [[prokaryotic]] [[Homology (biology)|homologue]] of the [[eukaryotic]] protein [[tubulin]]. The initials FtsZ mean \"'''F'''ilamenting  '''t'''emperature-'''s'''ensitive mutant '''Z'''\". The hypothesis was that cell division mutants of ''[[E. coli]]'' would grow as [[filamentation|filaments]] due to the inability of the daughter cells to separate from one another. FtsZ is found in almost all bacteria, many archaea, all chloroplasts and some mitochondria, where it is essential for cell division. FtsZ assembles the cytoskeletal scaffold of the Z ring that, along with additional proteins, constricts to divide the cell in two. \n\n== History ==\nIn the 1960s scientists screened for temperature sensitive mutations that blocked cell division at 42\u00b0 C. The mutant cells divided normally at 30\u00b0, but failed to divide at 42\u00b0. Continued growth without division produced long filamentous cells ('''F'''ilamenting '''t'''emperature '''s'''ensitive). Several such mutants were discovered and mapped to a locus originally named ''ftsA,'' which could be one or more genes''.'' In 1980 Lutkenhaus and Donachie<ref name=\"pmid6991482\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Lutkenhaus JF, Wolf-Watz H, Donachie WD | title = Organization of genes in the ftsA-envA region of the Escherichia coli genetic map and identification of a new fts locus (ftsZ) | journal = Journal of Bacteriology | volume = 142 | issue = 2 | pages = 615\u201320 | date = May 1980 | pmid = 6991482 | pmc = 294035 | url = https://jb.asm.org/content/jb/142/2/615.full.pdf | oclc = 678550294 }}</ref> showed that several of these mutations mapped to one gene, ''ftsA,'' but one well-characterized mutant, PAT84, originally discovered by Hirota et al,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hirota Y, Ryter A, Jacob F | title = Thermosensitive mutants of ''E. coli'' affected in the processes of DNA synthesis and cellular division | journal = Cold Spring Harbor Symposia on Quantitative Biology | volume = 33 | pages = 677\u201393 | date = 1968-01-01 | pmid = 4892005 | doi = 10.1101/sqb.1968.033.01.077 }}</ref> mapped to a separate, adjacent gene. They named this cell division gene ''ftsZ.'' In 1991 Bi and [[Joe Lutkenhaus|Lutkenhaus]] used immunogold electron microscopy to show that FtsZ localized to the invaginating septum at midcell.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Bi EF, Lutkenhaus J | title = FtsZ ring structure associated with division in ''Escherichia coli'' | journal = Nature | volume = 354 | issue = 6349 | pages = 161\u20134 | date = November 1991 | pmid = 1944597 | doi = 10.1038/354161a0 }}</ref>  Subsequently, the Losick and Margolin groups used immuno-fluorescence microscopy<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Levin PA, Losick R | title = Transcription factor Spo0A switches the localization of the cell division protein FtsZ from a medial to a bipolar pattern in Bacillus subtilis | journal = Genes & Development | volume = 10 | issue = 4 | pages = 478\u201388 | date = February 1996 | pmid = 8600030 | doi = 10.1101/gad.10.4.478 }}</ref> and GFP fusions<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ma X, Ehrhardt DW, Margolin W | title = Colocalization of cell division proteins FtsZ and FtsA to cytoskeletal structures in living ''Escherichia coli'' cells by using green fluorescent protein | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 93 | issue = 23 | pages = 12998\u20133003 | date = November 1996 | pmid = 8917533 | pmc = 24035 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.93.23.12998 }}</ref> to show that FtsZ assembled Z rings early in the cell cycle, well before the septum began to constrict.  Other division proteins then assemble onto the Z ring and constriction occurs in the last part of the cell cycle.\n\nIn 1992-3 three labs independently discovered that FtsZ was related to eukaryotic tubulin, which is the protein subunit that assembles into microtubules<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = RayChaudhuri D, Park JT | title = ''Escherichia coli'' cell-division gene ftsZ encodes a novel GTP-binding protein | journal = Nature | volume = 359 | issue = 6392 | pages = 251\u20134 | date = September 1992 | pmid = 1528267 | doi = 10.1038/359251a0 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = de Boer P, Crossley R, Rothfield L | title = The essential bacterial cell-division protein FtsZ is a GTPase | journal = Nature | volume = 359 | issue = 6392 | pages = 254\u20136 | date = September 1992 | pmid = 1528268 | doi = 10.1038/359254a0 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Mukherjee A, Dai K, Lutkenhaus J | title = ''Escherichia coli'' cell division protein FtsZ is a guanine nucleotide binding protein | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 90 | issue = 3 | pages = 1053\u20137 | date = February 1993 | pmid = 8430073 | pmc = 45809 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.90.3.1053 }}</ref>. This was the first discovery that bacteria have homologs of eukaryotic cytoskeletal proteins. Later work showed that FtsZ was present in, and essential for cell division, in almost all bacteria and in many but not all archaea. \n\nMitochondria and chloroplasts are eukaryotic orgenelles that originated as bacterial endosymbionts, so there was much interest in whether they use FtsZ for division. Chloroplast FtsZ was first discovered by Osteryoung<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Osteryoung KW, Vierling E | title = Conserved cell and organelle division | journal = Nature | volume = 376 | issue = 6540 | pages = 473\u20134 | date = August 1995 | pmid = 7637778 | doi = 10.1038/376473b0 }}</ref>, and it is now known that all chloroplasts use FtsZ for division. Mitochondrial FtsZ was discovered by Beech<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beech|first=P. L.|date=2000-02-18|title=Mitochondrial FtsZ in a Chromophyte Alga|journal=Science|volume=287|issue=5456|pages=1276\u20131279|doi=10.1126/science.287.5456.1276|pmid=10678836|issn=0036-8075|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/1dff1339f803c1e0a730c910886add8023d3ef34}}</ref> in an alga; FtsZ is used for mitochondrial division in some eukaryotes, while others have replaced it with a dynamin-based machinery. \u00a0\n\n== Function ==\n[[File:Filamentation 1.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Inhibition of FtsZ disrupts septum formation, resulting in [[filamentation]] of bacterial cells (top right of electron micrograph).]]\n\nDuring [[cell division]], FtsZ is the first protein to move to the division site, and is essential for recruiting other proteins that produce a new [[cell wall]] ([[Septum (cell biology)|septum]]) between the dividing cells.  FtsZ's role in cell division is analogous to that of [[actin]] in eukaryotic cell division, but, unlike the [[actin]]-[[myosin]] ring in eukaryotes, FtsZ has no known [[motor protein]] associated with it.  The origin of the [[cytokinesis|cytokinetic]] force, thus, remains unclear, but it is believed that the localized synthesis of new cell wall produces at least part of this force.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors = Coltharp C, Buss J, Plumer TM, Xiao, J |display-authors = 4 | title = Defining the rate-limiting processes of bacterial cytokinesis | journal = PNAS | volume = 113 | issue = 8 | pages = e1044-e1053 | date = February 2016 | pmid = 26831086 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.1514296113 }}</ref>   In liposomes Osawa (2009) showed FtsZ is capable of exerting a contractile force with no other proteins present.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Osawa M, Anderson DE, Erickson HP | title = Reconstitution of contractile FtsZ rings in liposomes | journal = Science | volume = 320 | issue = 5877 | pages = 792\u20134 | date = May 2008 | pmid = 18420899 | pmc = 2645864 | doi = 10.1126/science.1154520 }}</ref>\n\nErickson (2009) proposed how the roles of tubulin-like proteins and actin-like proteins in cell division became reversed in an evolutionary mystery.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Erickson HP | title = Evolution of the cytoskeleton | journal = BioEssays | volume = 29 | issue = 7 | pages = 668\u201377 | date = July 2007 | pmid = 17563102 | pmc = 2630885 | doi = 10.1002/bies.20601 }}</ref>\nThe use of the FtsZ ring in dividing [[chloroplast]]s and some [[mitochondrion|mitochondria]] further establishes their prokaryotic ancestry.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Leger MM, Petr\u016f M, \u017d\u00e1rsk\u00fd V, Eme L, Vl\u010dek \u010c, Harding T, Lang BF, Eli\u00e1\u0161 M, Dole\u017eal P, Roger AJ | display-authors = 6 | title = An ancestral bacterial division system is widespread in eukaryotic mitochondria | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 112 | issue = 33 | pages = 10239\u201346 | date = August 2015 | pmid = 25831547 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.1421392112 | pmc = 4547283 }}</ref> [[L-form bacteria]] that lack a [[cell wall]] do not require FtsZ for division, which implies that bacteria may have retained components of an ancestral mode of cell division.<ref name=\"pmid123455\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Leaver M, Dom\u00ednguez-Cuevas P, Coxhead JM, Daniel RA, Errington J | title = Life without a wall or division machine in Bacillus subtilis | journal = Nature | volume = 457 | issue = 7231 | pages = 849\u201353 | date = February 2009 | pmid = 19212404 | doi = 10.1038/nature07742 }}</ref>\n\nMuch is known about the dynamic polymerization activities of [[tubulin]] and [[microtubules]], but little is known about these activities in FtsZ.  While it is known that single-stranded [[tubulin]] protofilaments form into 13 stranded [[microtubules]], the multistranded structure of the FtsZ-containing Z-ring is not known. It is only speculated that the structure consists of overlapping protofilaments.  Nevertheless, recent work with purified FtsZ on supported lipid bilayers as well as imaging FtsZ in living bacterial cells  revealed that FtsZ protofilaments have polarity and move in one direction by [[treadmilling]] <ref name=\"pmid24316672\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Loose M, Mitchison TJ | title = The bacterial cell division proteins FtsA and FtsZ self-organize into dynamic cytoskeletal patterns | journal = Nature Cell Biology | volume = 16 | issue = 1 | pages = 38\u201346 | date = January 2014 | pmid = 24316672 | pmc = 4019675 | doi = 10.1038/ncb2885 }}</ref>(see also below).\n\nRecently, proteins similar to tubulin and FtsZ have been discovered in large plasmids found in ''Bacillus'' species. They are believed to function as components of [[segrosome]]s, which are multiprotein complexes that partition chromosomes/plasmids in bacteria. The plasmid homologs of tubulin/FtsZ seem to have conserved the ability to polymerize into filaments.\n\n=== The contractile ring ===\n[[File:FtsZ Filaments.svg|thumb|right|The Z-ring forms from smaller subunits of FtsZ filaments. These filaments may pull on each other and tighten to divide the cell.]]\n[[File:Zrings.png|thumb|upright|right|[[Super-resolution imaging|Super-resolution]] image of Z-rings (green) at different stages of constriction in two ''E. coli'' cells.]]\nFtsZ has the ability to bind to [[Guanosine triphosphate|GTP]] and also exhibits a [[GTPase]] domain that allows it to hydrolyze GTP to GDP and a phosphate group. ''In vivo'', FtsZ forms filaments with a repeating arrangement of subunits, all arranged head-to-tail.<ref name=\"pmid9442869\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Desai A, Mitchison TJ | title = Microtubule polymerization dynamics | journal = Annual Review of Cell and Developmental Biology | volume = 13 | pages = 83\u2013117 | year = 1997 | pmid = 9442869 | doi = 10.1146/annurev.cellbio.13.1.83 }}</ref> These filaments form a ring around the longitudinal midpoint, or septum, of the cell. This ring is called the Z-ring.\n\nThe GTP hydrolyzing activity of the protein is not essential to the formation of filaments or cell division. Mutants defective in GTPase activity often still divide, but sometimes form twisted and disordered septa.  It is unclear as to whether FtsZ actually provides the physical force that results in division or serves as a marker for other proteins to execute division.\n\nIf FtsZ does provide force that divides the cell, it may do so through the relative movement of subunits. Computer models and ''in vivo'' measurements suggest that single FtsZ filaments cannot sustain a length more than 30 subunits long. In this model, FtsZ scission force comes from the relative lateral movement of subunits.<ref name=\"pmid19116281\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Lan G, Daniels BR, Dobrowsky TM, Wirtz D, Sun SX | title = Condensation of FtsZ filaments can drive bacterial cell division | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 106 | issue = 1 | pages = 121\u20136 | date = January 2009 | pmid = 19116281 | pmc = 2629247 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0807963106 }}</ref> Lines of FtsZ would line up together parallel and pull on each other creating a \"cord\" of many strings that tightens itself.\n\nIn other models, FtsZ does not provide the contractile force but provides the cell a spatial scaffold for other proteins to execute the division of the cell. This is akin to the creating of a temporary structure by construction workers to access hard-to-reach places of a building. The temporary structure allows unfettered access and ensures that the workers can reach all places. If the temporary structure is not correctly built, the workers will not be able to reach certain places, and the building will be deficient.\n\nThe scaffold theory is supported by information that shows that the formation of the ring and localization to the membrane requires the concerted action of a number of accessory proteins. ZipA or the actin homologue [[FtsA]] permit initial FtsZ localization to the membrane.<ref name=\"pmid15752196\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Pichoff S, Lutkenhaus J | title = Tethering the Z ring to the membrane through a conserved membrane targeting sequence in FtsA | journal = Molecular Microbiology | volume = 55 | issue = 6 | pages = 1722\u201334 | date = March 2005 | pmid = 15752196 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2958.2005.04522.x }}</ref>  Following localization to the membrane, division proteins of the Fts family are recruited for ring assembly.<ref name=\"pmid12457697\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Buddelmeijer N, Beckwith J | title = Assembly of cell division proteins at the ''E. coli'' cell center | journal = Current Opinion in Microbiology | volume = 5 | issue = 6 | pages = 553\u20137 | date = December 2002 | pmid = 12457697 | doi = 10.1016/S1369-5274(02)00374-0 }}</ref> Many of these proteins, such as FtsW, FtsK, and FtsQ are involved in stabilization of the Z ring and may also be active participants in the scission event. The timing of Z-ring formation suggests the possibility of a spatial or temporal signal that permits the formation of FtsZ filaments.\n\nRecent super-resolution imaging in several species supports a dynamic scaffold model, in which small clusters of FtsZ protofilaments or protofilament bundles move unidirectionally around the ring's circumference by treadmilling, anchored to the membrane by [[FtsA]] and other FtsZ-specific membrane tethers.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Yang X, Lyu Z, Miguel A, McQuillen R, Huang KC, Xiao J | title = GTPase activity-coupled treadmilling of the bacterial tubulin FtsZ organizes septal cell wall synthesis | journal = Science | volume = 355 | issue = 6326 | pages = 744\u2013747 | date = February 2017 | pmid = 28209899 | doi = 10.1126/science.aak9995 | pmc = 5851775 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Bisson-Filho AW, Hsu YP, Squyres GR, Kuru E, Wu F, Jukes C, Sun Y, Dekker C, Holden S, VanNieuwenhze MS, Brun YV, Garner EC | display-authors = 6 | title = Treadmilling by FtsZ filaments drives peptidoglycan synthesis and bacterial cell division | journal = Science | volume = 355 | issue = 6326 | pages = 739\u2013743 | date = February 2017 | pmid = 28209898 | pmc = 5485650 | doi = 10.1126/science.aak9973 }}</ref>  The speed of treadmilling depends on the rate of GTP hydrolysis within the FtsZ protofilaments, but in ''[[Escherichia coli]]'', synthesis of the division septum remains the rate limiting step for cytokinesis.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors = Coltharp C, Buss J, Plumer TM, Xiao, J |display-authors = 4 | title = Defining the rate-limiting processes of bacterial cytokinesis | journal = PNAS | volume = 113 | issue = 8 | pages = e1044-e1053 | date = February 2016 | pmid = 26831086 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.1514296113 }}</ref> The treadmilling action of FtsZ is required for proper synthesis of the division septum by septal peptidoglycan synthesis enzymes, suggesting that these enzymes can track the growing ends of the filaments.\n\n=== Septal localization and intracellular signaling ===\n\nThe formation of the Z-ring closely coincides with cellular processes associated with replication. Z-ring formation coincides with the termination of genome replication in ''E. coli'' and 70% of chromosomal replication in ''[[B. subtilis]]''.<ref name=\"pmid11254978\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Harry EJ | title = Coordinating DNA replication with cell division: lessons from outgrowing spores | journal = Biochimie | volume = 83 | issue = 1 | pages = 75\u201381 | date = January 2001 | pmid = 11254978 | doi = 10.1016/S0300-9084(00)01220-7 }}</ref> The timing of Z-ring formation suggests the possibility of a spatial or temporal signal that permits the formation of FtsZ filaments. In ''[[Escherichia coli]]'', at least two negative regulators of FtsZ assembly form a bipolar gradient, such that the critical concentration of FtsZ required for FtsZ assembly is lowest at mid-cell between the two segregating chromosomes.  This type of regulation seems to occur in other species such as ''[[Bacillus subtilis]]'' and ''[[Caulobacter crescentus]]''.  However, other species including ''[[Streptococcus pneumoniae]]'' and ''[[Myxococcus xanthus]]'' seem to use positive regulators that stimulate FtsZ assembly at mid-cell.<ref name=\"pmid26029202\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Rowlett VW, Margolin W | title = The Min system and other nucleoid-independent regulators of Z ring positioning | journal = Frontiers in Microbiology | volume = 6 | issue =  | pages = 478 | year = 2015 | pmid = 26029202 | pmc = 4429545 | doi = 10.3389/fmicb.2015.00478 }}</ref>\n\n=== Communicating distress ===\n\nFtsZ polymerization is also linked to stressors like [[DNA damage]]. DNA damage induces a variety of proteins to be manufactured, one of them called [[SulA]].<ref name=\"pmid16310415\">{{cite journal | vauthors = He AS, Rohatgi PR, Hersh MN, Rosenberg SM | title = Roles of ''E. coli'' double-strand-break-repair proteins in stress-induced mutation | journal = DNA Repair | volume = 5 | issue = 2 | pages = 258\u201373 | date = February 2006 | pmid = 16310415 | pmc = 3685484 | doi = 10.1016/j.dnarep.2005.10.006 }}</ref>  SulA prevents the polymerization and GTPase activity of FtsZ. SulA accomplishes this task by binding to self-recognizing FtsZ sites. By sequestering FtsZ, the cell can directly link DNA damage to inhibiting cell division.<ref name=\"pmid9430638\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Mukherjee A, Lutkenhaus J | title = Dynamic assembly of FtsZ regulated by GTP hydrolysis | journal = The EMBO Journal | volume = 17 | issue = 2 | pages = 462\u20139 | date = January 1998 | pmid = 9430638 | pmc = 1170397 | doi = 10.1093/emboj/17.2.462 }}</ref>\n\n=== Preventing DNA damage ===\n\nLike SulA, there are other mechanisms that prevent cell division that would result in disrupted genetic information sent to daughter cells. So far, two proteins have been identified in ''E. coli'' and ''B. subtilis'' that prevent division over the nucleoid region: Noc and [[SlmA]]. Noc [[gene knockout]]s result in cells that divide without respect to the [[nucleoid]] region, resulting in its asymmetrical partitioning between the daughter cells. The mechanism is not well understood, but thought to involve sequestration of FtsZ, preventing [[polymerization]] over the nucleoid region.<ref name=\"pmid15210112\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Wu LJ, Errington J | title = Coordination of cell division and chromosome segregation by a nucleoid occlusion protein in Bacillus subtilis | journal = Cell | volume = 117 | issue = 7 | pages = 915\u201325 | date = June 2004 | pmid = 15210112 | doi = 10.1016/j.cell.2004.06.002 }}</ref> The mechanism used by SlmA to inhibit FtsZ polymerization over the nucleoid <ref name=\"pmid15916962\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Bernhardt TG, de Boer PA | title = SlmA, a nucleoid-associated, FtsZ binding protein required for blocking septal ring assembly over Chromosomes in ''E. coli'' | journal = Molecular Cell | volume = 18 | issue = 5 | pages = 555\u201364 | date = May 2005 | pmid = 15916962 | doi = 10.1016/j.molcel.2005.04.012 | pmc = 4428309 }}</ref> is better understood, and uses two separate steps.  One domain of SlmA binds to a FtsZ polymer, then a separate domain of SlmA severs the polymer <ref name=\"pmid25078077\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Du S, Lutkenhaus J | title = SlmA antagonism of FtsZ assembly employs a two-pronged mechanism like MinCD | journal = PLoS Genetics | volume = 10 | issue = 7 | pages = e1004460 | date = July 2014 | pmid = 25078077 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pgen.1004460 | pmc = 4117426 }}</ref>.  A similar mechanism is thought to be used by MinC, another inhibitor of FtsZ polymerization involved in positioning of the FtsZ ring.<ref name=\"pmid20132438\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Shen B, Lutkenhaus J | title = Examination of the interaction between FtsZ and MinCN in ''E. coli'' suggests how MinC disrupts Z rings | journal = Molecular Microbiology | volume = 75 | issue = 5 | pages = 1285\u201398 | date = March 2010 | pmid = 20132438 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2958.2010.07055.x }}</ref>\n\n== Clinical significance ==\n\nThe number of multidrug-resistant bacterial strains is currently increasing; thus, the determination of drug targets for the development of novel antimicrobial drugs is urgently needed. The potential role of FtsZ in the blockage of cell division makes FtsZ a highly attractive target for developing novel antibiotics. Researchers have been working on synthetic molecules and natural products as inhibitors of FtsZ. <ref>https://bjbms.org/ojs/index.php/bjbms/article/view/4597</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Fission (biology)]]\n* [[Divisome]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cytoskeletal Proteins}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ftsz}}\n[[Category:Bacterial proteins]]\n[[Category:Cytoskeleton]]\n", "name_user": "\u7531\u7406", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eClinical significance:adding citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FtsZ"}
{"title_page": "The Doon School Weekly", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox Newspaper |\nname = The Doon School Weekly |\nimage = The Doon School Weekly.jpg |\ntype = [[Weekly newspaper|Weekly]] [[student newspaper]] |\nowners = [[The Doon School]]|\nformat = [[Compact (newspaper)|Compact]] |\nfoundation = 1936 by [[Arthur Foot]]|\npolitical = None|\nlanguage = English|\npublisher  =Indian Public Schools' Society| \nheadquarters = Publications Room, Arts and Media Centre<br>[[The Doon School]]<br>[[Dehradun]]-248001<br>India |\ncirculation = c. 600 |\noclc = 224047237 |\nwebsite = http://www.doonschool.com/about-us/publications/past-weeklies/\n}}\n\n'''''The Doon School Weekly''''' (informally '''''Weekly''''') is a [[student newspaper]] produced by and for the students of [[The Doon School]].<ref>https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/put-him-down-for-doon</ref> Established in 1936, a year after the school's founding by the first headmaster [[Arthur Foot]], it is the flagship publication of the school. The newspaper's constitution grants it [[editorial independence]].<ref name=>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |last=Futehally |first=Laeeq |date=24 February 2002 |website=The Hindu |access-date=1 March 2012}}</ref> The paper, distributed every Saturday morning, carries a mix of reports on school activities, trips or expeditions, opinion pieces, critique of school policies, interviews of visiting speakers, student polls, crossword, cartoons, and creative writing, including short stories, poetry, satire or personal essays. The alumni keep up to date with the developments at school through the newspaper, which is also published online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2015/state-editions/a-beloved-teacher-of-the-doon-school.html|title=A beloved teacher of the Doon School|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref>  Notable alumni in the fields of literature, journalist, politics and academia have been former editors of the publication.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2019/state-editions/from-doon-school-to-jnanpith-award--amitav-ghosh---s-amazing-journey.html|title=From Doon School to Jnanpith Award: Amitav Ghosh\u2019s amazing journey|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestatesman.com/features/nature-cricket-literature-history-1502519395.html|title=Of nature, cricket, literature and history|date=29 October 2017}}</ref> The Weekly's sister publications at the school are ''Infinity'', ''The Doon School Information Review'', ''The Circle'', and ''The Yearbook''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kimonen|first=Eija|title=Education and Society in Comparative Context|year=2015|publisher=[[Springer Publishing]]|location=|isbn=9789463003735|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=SmM-CwAAQBAJ&|page=143|quote=In addition to producing a conventional yearbook, the students also produced other periodicals, such as the school's special publications: ''The Doon School Information Review''...and the scientific bi-annual ''The Echo'' and ''Cosmos''.}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nFounded by Arthu Foot in 1936, ''The Doon School Weekly'' is owned by Indian Public Schools' Society, the governing society of [[The Doon School]]. For the first three years of its existence, the newspaper was produced using a [[Cyclostyle (copier)|cyclostyle]], and then moved to a printing press.<ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ |page=120|quote=''The Doon School Weekly'' became an important feature of the school life and for many boys an education in itself. For the first three years the ''Weekly'' was cyclostyled. While this was not as neat as printing, it had the advantages that it was easy to reproduce drawings.}}</ref>  ''The Doon School Weekly'' has had a number of student contributors who went on to become authors, politicians and journalists. The list includes Booker Prize-nominee [[Amitav Ghosh]] (class of 1972); playwright, poet and novelist [[Vikram Seth]] (class of 1970); a number of staff writers for ''[[The Times of India]]'' newspaper such as [[Swaminathan Aiyar]] and veteran editor [[B G Verghese]], including broadcaster [[Karan Thapar]] (class of 1971), historian [[Ramchandra Guha]] (class of 1973), and politician [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]] (class of 1967); and Hindi language writer [[Vishvjit Singh]] (class of 1964); Foreign Secretary [[Uma Shankar Bajpai]] (class of 1936); [[Wajahat Habibullah]] (class of 1963) and [[Inder Pal Khosla]] (class of 1954); television-presenter [[Prannoy Roy]] and [[Tejeshwar Singh]] (class of 1965); and [[Mahmood Farooqui]] (class of 1979).<ref>[[Chhota Hazri]] Days:A Dosco's Yatra (2010) p.42</ref><ref>Chhota Hazri Days:A Dosco's Yatra (2010) p.153</ref><ref>The Doon School Chronicles (1996) p.55</ref> Former ''Doon School Weekly'' contributors have been editors, reporters or columnists for ''[[The Economic Times]]'', ''[[Forbes]]'', ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', ''[[Hindustan Times]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and ''[[The New York Times]]''. On April 14, 2018, the ''Weekly'' published its 2,500th edition, commemorating 82 years of its existence. The edition includes contributions from previous chief-editors such as Karan Thapar, Kanti Bajpai, Rahul Bhagat and Govind Dhar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7hK-gHFw8OUC&pg=PA119&dq=doon+school+weekly&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Nf77T_OPCoXzrQetzrDEBg&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=doon+school+weekly&f=false|title=The Corporeal Image: Film, Ethnography, and the Senses|first=David|last=MacDougall|date=20 July 2018|publisher=Princeton University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ywJr_YysE7wC&pg=PA25&dq=doon+school+weekly&hl=en&sa=X&ei=tf37T5eIOobqrQeHmsTgBg&ved=0CEoQ6AEwBDgK#v=onepage&q=doon+school+weekly&f=false|title=Psychology in International Perspective|first1=U. P.|last1=Gielen|first2=L.|last2=Loeb-Adler|first3=N.|last3=Milgram|date=1 January 1992|publisher=CRC Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Structure and operations==\nThe Weekly's editorial board is staffed by boys between year groups 9 and 12 at the school, with students in their final year leading the publication and taking key decisions. The selection process for the editorial board is competitive and consists of a written examination and personal interview with the board's leadership. The editor-in-chief, appointed by the school's administration, is the publication's chief executive and is responsible for content and day-to-day operations. He is assisted by the editors, the second-highest positions on the Editorial Board, who are also students in their final year of school. The length of a standard issue of the ''Weekly'' is 6-8 pages on legal-size ivory white paper. A special edition , released on the Saturday of the school's annual Founder's Day, is printed in the form of a magazine. The ''Weekly'' is accessible in print on the school's premises, and is also available online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/about-us/publications/past-weeklies/|title=Past Weeklies|website=Doon School}}</ref>\n\n==Notable former members==\n*[[Vikram Seth]] ('69, [[Editor-in-chief]])&nbsp;\u2013 Novelist, poet, librettist and playwright <ref name=\"auto\">'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.24</ref>\n*[[Swaminathan Aiyar]] ('60, [[Editor-in-chief]])&nbsp;\u2013 former India correspondent of ''[[The Economist]]''; editor of ''[[The Economic Times]]'' and ''[[The Times of India]]''\n*[[Amitav Ghosh]] ('73, [[Editor]])&nbsp;\u2013 Novelist, former editor of ''[[Indian Express]]'' <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*[[Ramchandra Guha]] ('73, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 Historian <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*[[Karan Thapar]] ('71, Editor-in-chief)&nbsp;\u2013 Broadcaster for [[CNBC]], [[BBC]] & [[CNN-IBN]] <ref name=\"auto1\">'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.25</ref>\n*[[Prannoy Roy]] ('64, [[Editor]])&nbsp;\u2013 Founder of [[New Delhi Television]] <ref>'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.27</ref>\n*[[Mani Shankar Aiyar]] ('58, Editor)&nbsp;\u2013 former [[Union Cabinet]] minister for [[Indian National Congress|Congress]] <ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Karan Singh]] ('49, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 [[Rajya Sabha]] member <ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Naveen Patnaik]] ('64, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 [[List of Chief Ministers of Odisha|Chief Minister of Odisha]] <ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Vishvjit Singh]] ('64, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 Poet and member of [[Indian National Congress]] <ref name=\"auto2\">'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.28</ref>\n*[[Wajahat Habibullah]] ('63, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 [[Information Commissioner|Chief Information Commissioner of India]] and chairman of the [[National Minorities Commission]] <ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n*[[B G Verghese]] ('58, Contributor) Editor of ''[[Indian Express]]'' (1982\u201386) and ''[[The Times of India]]'' (1986\u20132005); [[Ramon Magsaysay Award]] winner <ref name=\"auto3\">'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.33</ref>\n*[[Tejeshwar Singh]] ('65, Editor)&nbsp;\u2013 Indian publisher, newscaster <ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n*[[Vikram Chandra (NDTV)|Vikram Chandra]] ('83, Editor)&nbsp;\u2013 Broadcaster, news-presenter for [[New Delhi Television]] (NDTV) <ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n*[[Ardashir Vakil]] ('78, Editor)&nbsp;\u2013 Novelist <ref>'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.32</ref>\n*[[Govind Dhar]] ('97, Editor-in-Chief)&nbsp;\u2013 Travel journalist and magazine editor, former editor of the Robb Report India{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|30em}}\n===Further reading===\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=jc-9-rsFLxQC&pg=PA241&dq=doon+school+weekly&hl=en&sa=X&ei=t_j7T6HOFs_qrQe61NjUBg&ved=0CDwQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20weekly&f=false  Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School] by Sanjay Srivastava, Routledge (1995)\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=vUnF8fl2dzcC&pg=PA229&dq=doon+school+weekly&hl=en&sa=X&ei=t_j7T6HOFs_qrQe61NjUBg&ved=0CFMQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20weekly&f=false An Indian Englishman] by [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] (2008)\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |n=no |q=no |s=The Doon School Weekly |v=no |species=no |commons=Category:The Doon School Weekly }}\n{{Portal|Journalism}}\n*[http://www.doonschool.com Official website]\n*[http://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/clubs-societies/publications/past-weeklies/ Repository of past weeklies] on official website\n\n{{The Doon School}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doon School Weekly, The}}\n[[Category:The Doon School]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1936]]\n[[Category:Student newspapers published in India]]\n[[Category:Student magazines]]\n[[Category:High school newspapers]]\n[[Category:1936 establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox Newspaper |\nname = The Doon School Weekly |\nimage = The Doon School Weekly.jpg |\ntype = [[Weekly newspaper|Weekly]] [[student newspaper]] |\nowners = [[The Doon School]]|\nformat = [[Compact (newspaper)|Compact]] |\nfoundation = 1936 by [[Arthur Foot]]|\npolitical = None|\nlanguage = English|\npublisher  =Indian Public Schools' Society| \nheadquarters = Publications Room, Arts and Media Centre<br>[[The Doon School]]<br>[[Dehradun]]-248001<br>India |\ncirculation = c. 600 |\noclc = 224047237 |\nwebsite = http://www.doonschool.com/about-us/publications/past-weeklies/\n}}\n\n'''''The Doon School Weekly''''' (informally '''''Weekly''''') is a [[student newspaper]] produced by and for the students of [[The Doon School]].<ref>https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/put-him-down-for-doon</ref> Established in 1936, a year after the school's founding, by the first headmaster [[Arthur Foot]], it is the flagship publication of the school. The newspaper's constitution grants it [[editorial independence]].<ref name=>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |last=Futehally |first=Laeeq |date=24 February 2002 |website=The Hindu |access-date=1 March 2012}}</ref> The paper, distributed every Saturday morning, carries a mix of reports on school activities, trips or expeditions, opinion pieces, critique of school policies, interviews of visiting speakers, student polls, crossword, cartoons, and creative writing, including short stories, poetry, satire or personal essays. The alumni keep up to date with the developments at school through the newspaper, which is also published online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2015/state-editions/a-beloved-teacher-of-the-doon-school.html|title=A beloved teacher of the Doon School|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref>  Notable alumni in the fields of literature, journalist, politics and academia have been former editors of the publication.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2019/state-editions/from-doon-school-to-jnanpith-award--amitav-ghosh---s-amazing-journey.html|title=From Doon School to Jnanpith Award: Amitav Ghosh\u2019s amazing journey|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestatesman.com/features/nature-cricket-literature-history-1502519395.html|title=Of nature, cricket, literature and history|date=29 October 2017}}</ref> The Weekly's sister publications at the school are ''Infinity'', ''The Doon School Information Review'', ''The Circle'', and ''The Yearbook''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kimonen|first=Eija|title=Education and Society in Comparative Context|year=2015|publisher=[[Springer Publishing]]|location=|isbn=9789463003735|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=SmM-CwAAQBAJ&|page=143|quote=In addition to producing a conventional yearbook, the students also produced other periodicals, such as the school's special publications: ''The Doon School Information Review''...and the scientific bi-annual ''The Echo'' and ''Cosmos''.}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nFounded by Arthu Foot in 1936, ''The Doon School Weekly'' is owned by Indian Public Schools' Society, the governing society of [[The Doon School]]. For the first three years of its existence, the newspaper was produced using a [[Cyclostyle (copier)|cyclostyle]], and then moved to a printing press.<ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ |page=120|quote=''The Doon School Weekly'' became an important feature of the school life and for many boys an education in itself. For the first three years the ''Weekly'' was cyclostyled. While this was not as neat as printing, it had the advantages that it was easy to reproduce drawings.}}</ref>  ''The Doon School Weekly'' has had a number of student contributors who went on to become authors, politicians and journalists. The list includes Booker Prize-nominee [[Amitav Ghosh]] (class of 1972); playwright, poet and novelist [[Vikram Seth]] (class of 1970); a number of staff writers for ''[[The Times of India]]'' newspaper such as [[Swaminathan Aiyar]] and veteran editor [[B G Verghese]], including broadcaster [[Karan Thapar]] (class of 1971), historian [[Ramchandra Guha]] (class of 1973), and politician [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]] (class of 1967); and Hindi language writer [[Vishvjit Singh]] (class of 1964); Foreign Secretary [[Uma Shankar Bajpai]] (class of 1936); [[Wajahat Habibullah]] (class of 1963) and [[Inder Pal Khosla]] (class of 1954); television-presenter [[Prannoy Roy]] and [[Tejeshwar Singh]] (class of 1965); and [[Mahmood Farooqui]] (class of 1979).<ref>[[Chhota Hazri]] Days:A Dosco's Yatra (2010) p.42</ref><ref>Chhota Hazri Days:A Dosco's Yatra (2010) p.153</ref><ref>The Doon School Chronicles (1996) p.55</ref> Former ''Doon School Weekly'' contributors have been editors, reporters or columnists for ''[[The Economic Times]]'', ''[[Forbes]]'', ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', ''[[Hindustan Times]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and ''[[The New York Times]]''. On April 14, 2018, the ''Weekly'' published its 2,500th edition, commemorating 82 years of its existence. The edition includes contributions from previous chief-editors such as Karan Thapar, Kanti Bajpai, Rahul Bhagat and Govind Dhar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7hK-gHFw8OUC&pg=PA119&dq=doon+school+weekly&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Nf77T_OPCoXzrQetzrDEBg&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=doon+school+weekly&f=false|title=The Corporeal Image: Film, Ethnography, and the Senses|first=David|last=MacDougall|date=20 July 2018|publisher=Princeton University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ywJr_YysE7wC&pg=PA25&dq=doon+school+weekly&hl=en&sa=X&ei=tf37T5eIOobqrQeHmsTgBg&ved=0CEoQ6AEwBDgK#v=onepage&q=doon+school+weekly&f=false|title=Psychology in International Perspective|first1=U. P.|last1=Gielen|first2=L.|last2=Loeb-Adler|first3=N.|last3=Milgram|date=1 January 1992|publisher=CRC Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Structure and operations==\nThe Weekly's editorial board is staffed by boys between year groups 9 and 12 at the school, with students in their final year leading the publication and taking key decisions. The selection process for the editorial board is competitive and consists of a written examination and personal interview with the board's leadership. The editor-in-chief, appointed by the school's administration, is the publication's chief executive and is responsible for content and day-to-day operations. He is assisted by the editors, the second-highest positions on the Editorial Board, who are also students in their final year of school. The length of a standard issue of the ''Weekly'' is 6-8 pages on legal-size ivory white paper. A special edition , released on the Saturday of the school's annual Founder's Day, is printed in the form of a magazine. The ''Weekly'' is accessible in print on the school's premises, and is also available online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/about-us/publications/past-weeklies/|title=Past Weeklies|website=Doon School}}</ref>\n\n==Notable former members==\n*[[Vikram Seth]] ('69, [[Editor-in-chief]])&nbsp;\u2013 Novelist, poet, librettist and playwright <ref name=\"auto\">'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.24</ref>\n*[[Swaminathan Aiyar]] ('60, [[Editor-in-chief]])&nbsp;\u2013 former India correspondent of ''[[The Economist]]''; editor of ''[[The Economic Times]]'' and ''[[The Times of India]]''\n*[[Amitav Ghosh]] ('73, [[Editor]])&nbsp;\u2013 Novelist, former editor of ''[[Indian Express]]'' <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*[[Ramchandra Guha]] ('73, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 Historian <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*[[Karan Thapar]] ('71, Editor-in-chief)&nbsp;\u2013 Broadcaster for [[CNBC]], [[BBC]] & [[CNN-IBN]] <ref name=\"auto1\">'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.25</ref>\n*[[Prannoy Roy]] ('64, [[Editor]])&nbsp;\u2013 Founder of [[New Delhi Television]] <ref>'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.27</ref>\n*[[Mani Shankar Aiyar]] ('58, Editor)&nbsp;\u2013 former [[Union Cabinet]] minister for [[Indian National Congress|Congress]] <ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Karan Singh]] ('49, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 [[Rajya Sabha]] member <ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Naveen Patnaik]] ('64, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 [[List of Chief Ministers of Odisha|Chief Minister of Odisha]] <ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Vishvjit Singh]] ('64, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 Poet and member of [[Indian National Congress]] <ref name=\"auto2\">'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.28</ref>\n*[[Wajahat Habibullah]] ('63, Contributor)&nbsp;\u2013 [[Information Commissioner|Chief Information Commissioner of India]] and chairman of the [[National Minorities Commission]] <ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n*[[B G Verghese]] ('58, Contributor) Editor of ''[[Indian Express]]'' (1982\u201386) and ''[[The Times of India]]'' (1986\u20132005); [[Ramon Magsaysay Award]] winner <ref name=\"auto3\">'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.33</ref>\n*[[Tejeshwar Singh]] ('65, Editor)&nbsp;\u2013 Indian publisher, newscaster <ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n*[[Vikram Chandra (NDTV)|Vikram Chandra]] ('83, Editor)&nbsp;\u2013 Broadcaster, news-presenter for [[New Delhi Television]] (NDTV) <ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n*[[Ardashir Vakil]] ('78, Editor)&nbsp;\u2013 Novelist <ref>'History of the Weekly', The Doon School (2009) p.32</ref>\n*[[Govind Dhar]] ('97, Editor-in-Chief)&nbsp;\u2013 Travel journalist and magazine editor, former editor of the Robb Report India{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|30em}}\n===Further reading===\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=jc-9-rsFLxQC&pg=PA241&dq=doon+school+weekly&hl=en&sa=X&ei=t_j7T6HOFs_qrQe61NjUBg&ved=0CDwQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20weekly&f=false  Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School] by Sanjay Srivastava, Routledge (1995)\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=vUnF8fl2dzcC&pg=PA229&dq=doon+school+weekly&hl=en&sa=X&ei=t_j7T6HOFs_qrQe61NjUBg&ved=0CFMQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20weekly&f=false An Indian Englishman] by [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] (2008)\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |n=no |q=no |s=The Doon School Weekly |v=no |species=no |commons=Category:The Doon School Weekly }}\n{{Portal|Journalism}}\n*[http://www.doonschool.com Official website]\n*[http://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/clubs-societies/publications/past-weeklies/ Repository of past weeklies] on official website\n\n{{The Doon School}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doon School Weekly, The}}\n[[Category:The Doon School]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1936]]\n[[Category:Student newspapers published in India]]\n[[Category:Student magazines]]\n[[Category:High school newspapers]]\n[[Category:1936 establishments in India]]\n", "name_user": "Tabfelz", "label": "safe", "comment": "extra comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Doon_School_Weekly"}
{"title_page": "While the Women Are Sleeping", "text_new": "{{short description|2016 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = While the Women Are Sleeping\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Wayne Wang]]\n| producer       = Yukie Kito\n| writer         = Javier Marias (short story)<br />Michael Ray<br />[[Shinho Lee]]<br />Mami Sunada\n| starring       = [[Takeshi Kitano]]\n| music          = [[Youki Yamamoto]]\n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|2016|01|17|Waseda Film Festival|2016|2|27|Japan|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = \n| country        = Japan\n| language       = Japanese\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''While the Women Are Sleeping'''''|\u5973\u304c\u7720\u308b\u6642|lead=yes}} is a 2016 Japanese [[drama film]] directed by [[Wayne Wang]]. It was shown in the Panorama section at the [[66th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Panorama\">{{cite web |url=https://www.berlinale.de/en/presse/pressemitteilungen/alle/Alle-Detail_30868.html |title=Berlinale 2016: Panorama Special Opening Films, Christine Vachon to Receive Special Teddy Award and Films from Germany, Austria and Switzerland |accessdate=17 January 2016 |work=Berlinale}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Takeshi Kitano]]\n* [[Hidetoshi Nishijima (actor)|Hidetoshi Nishijima]]\n* [[Sayuri Oyamada]]\n* [[Shiori Kutsuna]]\n* [[Hirofumi Arai]]\n* [[Makiko Watanabe]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|4851852|While the Women Are Sleeping}}\n\n{{Wayne Wang}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:While The Women Are Sleeping}}\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:2016 drama films]]\n[[Category:Japanese films]]\n[[Category:Japanese drama films]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Wayne Wang]]\n{{2010s-Japan-film-stub}}\n{{2010s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2016 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Info