{"title_page": "Megan Ranney", "text_new": "{{short description|emergency physician}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Megan L. Ranney\n| workplaces        = [[Brown University]] <br> [[Rhode Island Hospital]]\n| thesis_title      = Surveys in injury research : their application to unintentional and intentional injury prevention\n| thesis_url        = http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/744300436\n| thesis_year       = 2010\n| alma_mater        = [[Harvard University]] (BA) <br> [[Columbia University]] (MD) <br> Brown University (MPH)\n}}\n\n'''Megan L. Ranney''' is an American emergency physician who works at the [[Rhode Island Hospital]] and is an Associate Professor at [[Brown University]]. During the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] Ranney brought public attention to the deficit of protective equipment for [[United States]] frontline workers. She launched the grassroots organisation #GetUsPPE to collect, create and distribute [[personal protective equipment]] around the United States.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nRanney studied history of science at [[Harvard University]] and graduated ''[[summa cum laude]]'' in 1997.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://vivo.brown.edu/display/mranney|title=Ranney, Megan|website=vivo.brown.edu|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> After graduating Ranney joined the [[Peace Corps]], where she supported programmes in the [[Ivory Coast]].<ref name=\":0\" /> On returning to the United States, Ranney joined [[Columbia University Vagelos College of Physicians and Surgeons]] as a medical student, where she graduated as a member of both Alpha Omega Alpha and the Gold Humanism Honor Society.<ref name=\":0\" /> She completed her internship, residency and chief residency in emergency medicine at Brown.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2010 Ranney earned her [[Master's in Public Health]], where she studied injury prevention.<ref>{{Cite thesis|title=Surveys in injury research: their application to unintentional and intentional injury prevention|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/surveys-in-injury-research-their-application-to-unintentional-and-intentional-injury-prevention/oclc/744300436|date=2010|language=English|first=Megan L|last=Ranney}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.browndailyherald.com/2020/04/02/physicians-perspectives-impacts-ppe-shortages-covid-19-lifespan/|title=Physicians\u2019 perspectives: Impacts of PPE shortages, COVID-19 on Lifespan|last=Ibrahim|first=Rahma|date=2020-04-02|website=Brown Daily Herald|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== Research and career ==\nRanney worked as a physician at the [[Rhode Island Hospital]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://eastgreenwichnews.com/eg-doctor-becomes-national-face-for-ppe/|title=EG Doctor Becomes National Face for PPE|last=McNamara|first=Elizabeth|date=2020-04-04|website=East Greenwich News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Here she experienced the destruction that can be caused by the possession of [[gun]]s. She used her platform to start conversations about guns being a [[public health]] concerns.<ref name=\":2\" /> After the [[2018 United States gun violence protests]], the [[National Rifle Association]] tweeted \"Someone should tell self-important anti-gun doctors to stay in their lane\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hbr.org/2019/10/how-doctors-can-help-prevent-gun-violence|title=How Doctors Can Help Prevent Gun Violence|last=|first=|date=|website=HBR|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Ranney helped found the American Foundation for Firearm Injury Reduction in Medicine, for which she serves as research officer.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://affirmresearch.org/|title=Home|website=AFFIRM Research|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> The following year, Ranney delivered a [[TED (conference)|TED]] talk where she discussed how healthcare professionals can help to solve America's gun problem.<ref>{{Citation|last=Ranney|first=Megan|title=How the public health approach can solve gun violence|url=https://www.ted.com/talks/megan_ranney_how_the_public_health_approach_can_solve_gun_violence|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>''\n\n=== #GetUsPPE ===\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Ranney drew public attention to the lack of [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE) for frontline staff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/why-would-hospitals-forbid-physicians-and-nurses-from-wearing-masks/|title=Why Would Hospitals Forbid Physicians and Nurses from Wearing Masks?|last=Sathya|first=Chethan|website=Scientific American Blog Network|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/20/medical-supply-shortage-coronavirus|title=Donations And DIY Masks: Health Care Workers Get Creative With '#GetMePPE'|website=www.wbur.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> Ranney pointed out that alongside escalating [[SARS-CoV-2]] patient numbers, the protocols, treatment options and [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|Centers for Disease Control]] (CDC) recommendations changed everyday.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/03/31/doctors-hospitals-front-lines-coronavirus/|title=As coronavirus spreads, ER doctors warn 'the worst of it has not hit us yet'|date=2020-03-31|website=STAT|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medicinenet.com/script/main/art.asp?articlekey=229747|title=Healthcare Workers Feel Betrayed in Coronavirus Disaster - MedicineNet Health News|website=MedicineNet|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> At the time she was based at the Rhode Island Hospital in [[Providence, Rhode Island]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/03/31/doctors-hospitals-front-lines-coronavirus/|title=As coronavirus spreads, ER doctors warn 'the worst of it has not hit us yet'|date=2020-03-31|website=STAT|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Ranney described shortages in PPE in ''[[The New England Journal of Medicine]]'', where she called for [[Donald Trump]] to invoke the [[Defense Production Act of 1950|Defense Production Act]] and ensure private companies to start manufacturing PPE.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Ranney|first=Megan L.|last2=Griffeth|first2=Valerie|last3=Jha|first3=Ashish K.|date=2020-03-25|title=Critical Supply Shortages \u2014 The Need for Ventilators and Personal Protective Equipment during the Covid-19 Pandemic|url=https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMp2006141|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=0|issue=0|pages=null|doi=10.1056/NEJMp2006141|issn=0028-4793}}</ref> She requested that private-sector companies start to manufacture [[N95 mask]]s, and that the [[Food and Drug Administration]] relaxed the standards to allow healthcare workers to have faster access to protective clothing.<ref name=\":3\" /> She has asked whether local governments could better coordinate the collection of PPE from existing stockpiles.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/31/824851191/answering-your-coronavirus-questions-death-toll-treating-covid-19-and-testing-sc|title=Answering Your Coronavirus Questions: Death Toll, Treating COVID-19 And Testing Scams|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Ma|first=Michelle|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-you-can-donate-protective-equipment-to-help-hospitals-fight-coronavirus-11585323638|title=How You Can Donate Protective Equipment to Help Hospitals Fight Coronavirus|date=2020-04-03|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> In March 2020, Ranney submitted recommendations to the [[federal government of the United States]] on what priorities should be included in the [[COVID-19 Stimulus Bill]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.healthaffairs.org/do/10.1377/hblog20200312.363618/full/|title=Health Care Priorities For A COVID-19 Stimulus Bill: Recommendations To The Administration, Congress, And Other Federal, State And Local Leaders From Public Health, Medical, Policy And Legal Experts {{!}} Health Affairs|website=www.healthaffairs.org|language=en|doi=10.1377/hblog20200312.363618/full/|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Her recommendations included focussing on health security, protecting the health of all American's, particularly those from minoritised backgrounds, and to invest money in public health initiatives.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nRanney worked with [[Shuhan He]], a doctor at [[Massachusetts General Hospital]], to create the organisation #GetUsPPE.<ref name=\":2\" /> GetUsPPE is a grassroots collective of engineers, medical professionals and volunteers who look to locate, create and distribute equipment to Americans in need.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/getusppe-announces-perspective-piece-in-the-new-england-journal-of-medicine-on-medical-equipment-shortage-crisis-due-to-covid-19-301030994.html|title=#GetUsPPE Announces Perspective Piece in the New England Journal of Medicine on Medical Equipment Shortage Crisis Due to Covid-19|last=#GetUsPPE|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> #GetUsPPE called for the pubic to donate money and resources to protect frontline physicians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-ppe-gear-equipment-n95-masks-medical-doctors-nurses/|title=Doctors and nurses desperate for protective gear are begging the public to donate it|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Amongst other donations, Ranney collected 4,000 N95 masks from colleagues at Brown University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brown.edu/news/2020-04-01/donations-0|title=Brown donates lab supplies and protective equipment in COVID fight|website=Brown University|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020 Ranney lost her colleague, [[Frank Gabrin]], to the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus disease]]. He was the first emergency doctor to die from such symptoms.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/news/490701-us-emergency-room-doctor-dies-after-coronavirus-symptoms|title=US emergency room doctor dies after coronavirus symptoms|last=Klar|first=Rebecca|date=2020-04-01|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Ranney was quoted by ''[[Meet the Press]]'' as saying, \"He was a leader within the emergency room field. ... Unless our government steps up & gets us the protective equipment we need, he will be the first of many of my colleagues,\".<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nRanney is married to Chuck Ranney, with whom she has two children.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{scholia|author}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rannet, Megan}}\n\n[[Category:Brown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Brown University faculty]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Women physicians]]\n[[Category:American women physicians]]\n[[Category:Science communicators]]\n[[Category:American emergency physicians]]\n[[Category:Emergency physicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century women physicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|emergency physician}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Megan L. Ranney\n| workplaces        = [[Brown University]] <br> [[Rhode Island Hospital]]\n| thesis_title      = Surveys in injury research : their application to unintentional and intentional injury prevention\n| thesis_url        = http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/744300436\n| thesis_year       = 2010\n| alma_mater        = [[Harvard University]] (BA) <br> [[Columbia University]] (MD) <br> Brown University (MPH)\n}}\n\n'''Megan L. Ranney''' is an American emergency physician who works at the [[Rhode Island Hospital]] and is osan Associate Professor at [[Brown University]]. During the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] Ranney brought public attention to the deficit of protective equipment for [[United States]] frontline workers. She launched the grassroots organisation #GetUsPPE to collect, create and distribute [[personal protective equipment]] around the United States.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nRanney studied history of science at [[Harvard University]] and graduated ''[[summa cum laude]]'' in 1997.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://vivo.brown.edu/display/mranney|title=Ranney, Megan|website=vivo.brown.edu|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> After graduating Ranney joined the [[Peace Corps]], where she supported programmes in the [[Ivory Coast]].<ref name=\":0\" /> On returning to the United States, Ranney joined [[Columbia University Vagelos College of Physicians and Surgeons]] as a medical student, where she graduated as a member of both Alpha Omega Alpha and the Gold Humanism Honor Society.<ref name=\":0\" /> She completed her internship, residency and chief residency in emergency medicine at Brown.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2010 Ranney earned her [[Master's in Public Health]], where she studied injury prevention.<ref>{{Cite thesis|title=Surveys in injury research: their application to unintentional and intentional injury prevention|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/surveys-in-injury-research-their-application-to-unintentional-and-intentional-injury-prevention/oclc/744300436|date=2010|language=English|first=Megan L|last=Ranney}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.browndailyherald.com/2020/04/02/physicians-perspectives-impacts-ppe-shortages-covid-19-lifespan/|title=Physicians\u2019 perspectives: Impacts of PPE shortages, COVID-19 on Lifespan|last=Ibrahim|first=Rahma|date=2020-04-02|website=Brown Daily Herald|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== Research and career ==\nRanney worked as a physician at the [[Rhode Island Hospital]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://eastgreenwichnews.com/eg-doctor-becomes-national-face-for-ppe/|title=EG Doctor Becomes National Face for PPE|last=McNamara|first=Elizabeth|date=2020-04-04|website=East Greenwich News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Here she experienced the destruction that can be caused by the possession of [[gun]]s. She used her platform to start conversations about guns being a [[public health]] concerns.<ref name=\":2\" /> After the [[2018 United States gun violence protests]], the [[National Rifle Association]] tweeted \"Someone should tell self-important anti-gun doctors to stay in their lane\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hbr.org/2019/10/how-doctors-can-help-prevent-gun-violence|title=How Doctors Can Help Prevent Gun Violence|last=|first=|date=|website=HBR|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Ranney helped found the American Foundation for Firearm Injury Reduction in Medicine, for which she serves as research officer.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://affirmresearch.org/|title=Home|website=AFFIRM Research|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> The following year, Ranney delivered a [[TED (conference)|TED]] talk where she discussed how healthcare professionals can help to solve America's gun problem.<ref>{{Citation|last=Ranney|first=Megan|title=How the public health approach can solve gun violence|url=https://www.ted.com/talks/megan_ranney_how_the_public_health_approach_can_solve_gun_violence|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>''\n\n=== #GetUsPPE ===\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Ranney drew public attention to the lack of [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE) for frontline staff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/why-would-hospitals-forbid-physicians-and-nurses-from-wearing-masks/|title=Why Would Hospitals Forbid Physicians and Nurses from Wearing Masks?|last=Sathya|first=Chethan|website=Scientific American Blog Network|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/20/medical-supply-shortage-coronavirus|title=Donations And DIY Masks: Health Care Workers Get Creative With '#GetMePPE'|website=www.wbur.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> Ranney pointed out that alongside escalating [[SARS-CoV-2]] patient numbers, the protocols, treatment options and [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|Centers for Disease Control]] (CDC) recommendations changed everyday.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/03/31/doctors-hospitals-front-lines-coronavirus/|title=As coronavirus spreads, ER doctors warn 'the worst of it has not hit us yet'|date=2020-03-31|website=STAT|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medicinenet.com/script/main/art.asp?articlekey=229747|title=Healthcare Workers Feel Betrayed in Coronavirus Disaster - MedicineNet Health News|website=MedicineNet|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> At the time she was based at the Rhode Island Hospital in [[Providence, Rhode Island]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/03/31/doctors-hospitals-front-lines-coronavirus/|title=As coronavirus spreads, ER doctors warn 'the worst of it has not hit us yet'|date=2020-03-31|website=STAT|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Ranney described shortages in PPE in ''[[The New England Journal of Medicine]]'', where she called for [[Donald Trump]] to invoke the [[Defense Production Act of 1950|Defense Production Act]] and ensure private companies to start manufacturing PPE.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Ranney|first=Megan L.|last2=Griffeth|first2=Valerie|last3=Jha|first3=Ashish K.|date=2020-03-25|title=Critical Supply Shortages \u2014 The Need for Ventilators and Personal Protective Equipment during the Covid-19 Pandemic|url=https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMp2006141|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=0|issue=0|pages=null|doi=10.1056/NEJMp2006141|issn=0028-4793}}</ref> She requested that private-sector companies start to manufacture [[N95 mask]]s, and that the [[Food and Drug Administration]] relaxed the standards to allow healthcare workers to have faster access to protective clothing.<ref name=\":3\" /> She has asked whether local governments could better coordinate the collection of PPE from existing stockpiles.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/31/824851191/answering-your-coronavirus-questions-death-toll-treating-covid-19-and-testing-sc|title=Answering Your Coronavirus Questions: Death Toll, Treating COVID-19 And Testing Scams|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Ma|first=Michelle|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-you-can-donate-protective-equipment-to-help-hospitals-fight-coronavirus-11585323638|title=How You Can Donate Protective Equipment to Help Hospitals Fight Coronavirus|date=2020-04-03|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> In March 2020, Ranney submitted recommendations to the [[federal government of the United States]] on what priorities should be included in the [[COVID-19 Stimulus Bill]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.healthaffairs.org/do/10.1377/hblog20200312.363618/full/|title=Health Care Priorities For A COVID-19 Stimulus Bill: Recommendations To The Administration, Congress, And Other Federal, State And Local Leaders From Public Health, Medical, Policy And Legal Experts {{!}} Health Affairs|website=www.healthaffairs.org|language=en|doi=10.1377/hblog20200312.363618/full/|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Her recommendations included focussing on health security, protecting the health of all American's, particularly those from minoritised backgrounds, and to invest money in public health initiatives.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nRanney worked with [[Shuhan He]], a doctor at [[Massachusetts General Hospital]], to create the organisation #GetUsPPE.<ref name=\":2\" /> GetUsPPE is a grassroots collective of engineers, medical professionals and volunteers who look to locate, create and distribute equipment to Americans in need.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/getusppe-announces-perspective-piece-in-the-new-england-journal-of-medicine-on-medical-equipment-shortage-crisis-due-to-covid-19-301030994.html|title=#GetUsPPE Announces Perspective Piece in the New England Journal of Medicine on Medical Equipment Shortage Crisis Due to Covid-19|last=#GetUsPPE|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> #GetUsPPE called for the pubic to donate money and resources to protect frontline physicians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-ppe-gear-equipment-n95-masks-medical-doctors-nurses/|title=Doctors and nurses desperate for protective gear are begging the public to donate it|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Amongst other donations, Ranney collected 4,000 N95 masks from colleagues at Brown University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brown.edu/news/2020-04-01/donations-0|title=Brown donates lab supplies and protective equipment in COVID fight|website=Brown University|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020 Ranney lost her colleague, [[Frank Gabrin]], to the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus disease]]. He was the first emergency doctor to die from such symptoms.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/news/490701-us-emergency-room-doctor-dies-after-coronavirus-symptoms|title=US emergency room doctor dies after coronavirus symptoms|last=Klar|first=Rebecca|date=2020-04-01|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Ranney was quoted by ''[[Meet the Press]]'' as saying, \"He was a leader within the emergency room field. ... Unless our government steps up & gets us the protective equipment we need, he will be the first of many of my colleagues,\".<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nRanney is married to Chuck Ranney, with whom she has two children.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{scholia|author}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rannet, Megan}}\n\n[[Category:Brown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Brown University faculty]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Women physicians]]\n[[Category:American women physicians]]\n[[Category:Science communicators]]\n[[Category:American emergency physicians]]\n[[Category:Emergency physicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century women physicians]]\n", "name_user": "Melcous", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Megan_Ranney"}
